<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: SUPERVISORS FORMALLY OPPOSE PROP. 188 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JULIE FIELDS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Joining cities and counties throughout California, the Ventura County Board of 
Supervisors has passed a resolution opposing a statewide ballot initiative that 
would wipe out local restrictions on smoking in public places. 
</P>
<P>
 Proposition 188, which is backed by tobacco giant Philip Morris Inc., would 
replace local smoking ordinances with a more lax statewide anti-smoking law. 
Only the state Legislature could amend the law, which would require a 
two-thirds vote. 
</P>
<P>
 The board approved its resolution opposing the measure during its meeting 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 Ventura County passed a strict anti-smoking ordinance in November. Other 
cities in the county, including Camarillo, Ojai and Ventura, also have passed 
similar ordinances during the past year. JULIE FIELDS 
</P>
</TEXT>
